[[File:Moro-jinja (Nagareyama) ninotorii.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Second torii]]
'''Moro Shrine'''（もろじんじゃ）is a shrine in {{ill|lt=Nagareyama|Q328625|qid=Q328625|1=Nagareyama}}, {{ill|lt=Chiba Prefecture|Q80011|qid=Q80011|1=Chiba Prefecture}}. Its former name was "Miwa Shrine." It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}{{ill|lt=Ronsha|Q135022904|qid=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}, and under the former {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was a {{ill|lt=Sonsha|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* {{ill|qid=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi|Q10936701|qid=Q10936701|qid=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōmononushi}}（おおものぬしのみこと）

=== History ===
In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, it is listed as "{{ill|lt=Shimōsa Province|Q1053695|qid=Q1053695|1=Shimōsa Province}}{{ill|lt=Katsushika District|Q11621089|qid=Q11621089|1=Katsushika district}} Moro Shrine" as a small shrine, and is regarded as one candidate shrine. There are two other candidate shrines (in {{ill|lt=Matsudo|Q320943|qid=Q320943|1=Matsudo}} and {{ill|lt=Funabashi|Q271417|qid=Q271417|1=Funabashi}})（see "{{ill|lt=Moro Shrine|Q11617025|qid=Q11617025|1=Moro Shrine}}"）.
The first appearance of Moro Shrine itself in the national chronicles is in the entry for 12 November, Jōgan 13 (817), in the {{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|qid=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}: "Moro-no-kami was granted {{ill|lt=court rank for deities|Q11591025|qid=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} Senior Fifth Rank, Upper." Later, on 25 September, Gangyō 3（{{ill|lt=879|Q25001|qid=Q25001|1=879}}）, it was granted Senior Fifth Rank, Upper.

The founding of the shrine is unknown. Its deity Ōmononushi-no-Mikoto is considered a divided spirit from {{ill|lt=Ōmiwa Shrine|Q705542|qid=Q705542|1=Ōmiwa Shrine}} on {{ill|lt=Mount Miwa|Q860627|qid=Q860627|1=Mount Miwa}} in {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|qid=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}, and the shrine name "Moro" is thought to come from "Moro" in the old name of Mt. Miwa, "Mimoro-yama."<ref>There is also a theory that it derives from "mori," meaning a sacred grove where gods dwell.</ref> For this reason, the plateau where the shrine stands is also called "Mt. Miwa"（{{ill|lt=Miwano-yama|Q11357427|qid=Q11357427|1=Miwano-yama}}）. From remains of a jingū-ji, old torii remains on the former western approach at Hirai, and place-name origins such as Yagi-gō, it is inferred that the shrine once had an extensive {{ill|lt=sacred precinct|Q11588853|qid=Q11588853|1=shin'iki}}.

In {{ill|lt=Keichō|Q1328185|qid=Q1328185|1=Keichō}} 3（{{ill|lt=1598|Q6800|qid=Q6800|1=1598}}）, excavation of the {{ill|lt=Edo River|Q1194505|qid=Q1194505|1=Edo River}} divided the sacred area. This shrine lies on the east bank. As a result, during the {{ill|lt=Genna|Q635245|qid=Q635245|lt=Genna|1=Genna}} era a branch shrine was established on the west bank, and {{ill|lt=Miwa Shrine (Yoshikawa)|Q119929491|qid=Q119929491|lt=Miwa Shrine|1=Miwa Shrine}} was founded. Also, the shrine received an annual offering of 25 koku from the {{ill|lt=Tokugawa shogunate|Q205662|qid=Q205662|1=Tokugawa shogunate}}.

=== Precincts ===
* Honden
* Haiden - the roof tiles were re-laid in Heisei 7.

Adjacent to the precincts are remains of a {{ill|lt=jingū-ji|Q1074971|qid=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}}.

=== Ritual ===
* Jingara-mochi
: At the Obisha (New Year rite) on {{ill|lt=January 8|Q2234|qid=Q2234|1=January 8}}, kagami-mochi is offered before the deity and then parishioners tear it apart. The way it breaks was used to divine the year's harvest. It is designated by {{ill|lt=Nagareyama|Q328625|qid=Q328625|1=Nagareyama}} as an intangible folk cultural property.

=== Cultural properties ===
=== Nagareyama-designated intangible folk cultural property ===
